result.execSummary:
The defendant Jericho Tarane Harris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Jericho Tarane Harris in court with attorney Torrie R. Williams.  Daniel J. Gabler appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk ssm.  Case calendared for jury trial.  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered charge amended to DISORDERLY CONDUCT contrary to County Ordinance 63.01 to which the defendant entered a plea of no contest.  Court found the defendant guilty and ordered a forfeiture in the amount of $325.00 including costs to be paid by 08-31-2015 or, if not paid, convert to a civil judgment.
